<BLOCKQUOTE>Posted by
Puggles of Bertoxxulous on 16:47:49 9/1/1999 from 24.4.252.247:<p>
In reply to: <a href="http://cor.simplenet.com/Mage/mageboard.mv?parm_func=showmsg+parm_msgnum=1000152">Dumb Question, but hey...Im new</a> posted by 
Diarmuid on 10:17:50 8/31/1999 from 130.110.2.242:<p>
: Why is it that Magician's summon pet spells end at lvl 20,<br>:  or 29 whatever it is, and yet necro's get summon pet spel<br>: ls all the way through their 49th lvl spells?  And are the<br>:  burnouts, worth it, or do they get yer pet killed too fas<br>: t?<br><br>The Burnout spells are really "special use" spells. I don't just summon an elemental and put Burnout on it, because I often want it to be able to regenerate as fast as possible so it's ready for the next scirmish I have to fight. But when I am in a group of 6 or so, well balanced (with tanks) then I'll always put the level 12 Burnout spell on my pet. Why not add damage to its output if it's not going to be taking hits?<br><br>Burnout II is a harder question. I have had situations where we were going to go in and have to kill something ASAP or we'd all die too. (The froglok ghoul assassin comes to mind, in lower guk) where I memorized Burnout II as a attack spell. Dropped shock of spikes off my list, just so I could give my pet that extra 5 points a round. My pet died during the fighting, but it did a lot of damage, that much I'm sure of. It was more useful that way than it would have been had it just been with burnout I or no burnout at all. (We won the fight, by the way, and got a guise for one of our tanks =p)<br><br>Burnout III is a spell that makes your pet so wild that it would be something you put on DURING a battle with someone like Vox or more in perspective the froglok king or soluesk kobold king. But their uses are pretty much limited like that.<br><br>Puggles Snuggles<br>36 Magician<br>Bertoxxulous
</MvEVAL>
</BLOCKQUOTE><hr width=90%><p>
